findings.description:
The PR Status command contains a ~30-line inline success/error telemetry flush block that duplicates the logic already extracted into flushTelemetrySuccess/flushTelemetryError in telemetryLifecycle.ts. The pr/status.ts inner catch block manually calls metrics.observe, metrics.increment, metrics.flush, commandSpan.setAttribute, commandSpan.end, traceManager.flush, ensureTelemetryReferences, logger.error, and logger.flush in the exact same sequence as the shared helper — but without using it.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// src/cli/commands/pr/status.ts lines 256-289 (error path)
const duration = Date.now() - startTime;
metrics.observe(StandardMetrics.COMMAND_EXECUTION_DURATION_MS, duration, { command: 'pr.status' });
metrics.increment(StandardMetrics.COMMAND_INVOCATIONS_TOTAL, { command: 'pr.status', exit_code: '1' });
await metrics.flush();
commandSpan.setAttribute('exit_code', 1);
commandSpan.setAttribute('error', true);
// ... plus span end, traceManager.flush, ensureTelemetryReferences, logger.error, logger.flush
--- code end ---

The same pattern exists in the success path (lines 226-249). The sibling pr/create.ts and pr/reviewers.ts and pr/disable-auto-merge.ts all use the shared flushTelemetrySuccess/flushTelemetryError correctly. The pr/status.ts command is the outlier that was not migrated.

The block that builds the mergedConfig, validates execution config existence, calls buildExecutionStrategies, constructs CLIExecutionEngine, and validates prerequisites is copy-pasted nearly identically in start.ts (runTaskExecution, lines 610-655) and resume.ts (lines 328-358). Both contain the identical guard:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// Both files
if (!mergedConfig.execution) {
  throw new Error(
    'Execution config is required. Ensure your .codepipe/config.json includes an "execution" section.'
  );
}
const strategies = await buildExecutionStrategies(mergedConfig.execution, logger);
const executionEngine = new CLIExecutionEngine({ runDir, config: mergedConfig, strategies, dryRun: false, logger, telemetry });
const prereqResult = await executionEngine.validatePrerequisites();
if (!prereqResult.valid) { throw new ... }
if (prereqResult.warnings.length > 0) { prereqResult.warnings.forEach(w => logger.warn(w)); }
--- code end ---

The only differences are error type (CliError in start.ts, plain Error in resume.ts) and the max_parallel_tasks merge logic. This ~30-line block should be a shared function.

The following 10-line block is copy-pasted verbatim in pr/create.ts, pr/status.ts, pr/reviewers.ts, and pr/disable-auto-merge.ts:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
const settings = await resolveRunDirectorySettings();
const featureId = await selectFeatureId(settings.baseDir, typedFlags.feature);
if (!featureId) {
  this.error('No feature run directory found. Run "codepipe start" first.', { exit: PRExitCode.VALIDATION_ERROR });
}
if (typedFlags.feature && featureId !== typedFlags.feature) {
  this.error(`Feature run directory not found: ${typedFlags.feature}`, { exit: PRExitCode.VALIDATION_ERROR });
}
const context = await loadPRContext(settings.baseDir, featureId, settings.config!, false);
--- code end ---

This pattern appears in all four PR subcommands with no variation. It should be a shared helper.

Nine commands contain two near-identical guard statements back to back after selectFeatureId:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
if (!featureId) {
  this.error('No feature run directory found. Run "codepipe start" first.', { exit: 10 });
}
if (typedFlags.feature && featureId !== typedFlags.feature) {
  this.error(`Feature run directory not found: ${typedFlags.feature}`, { exit: 10 });
}
--- code end ---

Files with this identical guard: rate-limits.ts, validate.ts, research/create.ts, research/list.ts, context/summarize.ts, pr/create.ts, pr/status.ts, pr/reviewers.ts, pr/disable-auto-merge.ts. The PR commands use PRExitCode.VALIDATION_ERROR (which equals 10) and the non-PR commands use exit code 10 directly, but the logic is otherwise identical. selectFeatureId already exists as a shared helper — this guard should be folded into it or a wrapper.

The pattern for re-throwing oclif errors to preserve exit codes appears in 12 command files:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// Re-throw oclif errors to preserve exit codes
if (error && typeof error === 'object' && 'oclif' in error) {
  throw error;
}
--- code end ---

Affected files: plan.ts, doctor.ts, pr/create.ts, pr/reviewers.ts, pr/disable-auto-merge.ts, pr/status.ts, status/index.ts, validate.ts, rate-limits.ts, resume.ts, context/summarize.ts, init.ts. This guard belongs in a shared rethrowIfOclifError utility or as part of the flushTelemetryError helper itself.

Eight command files declare the same five or six telemetry variable block at the top of run():

--- code begin (reference only) ---
let logger: StructuredLogger | undefined;
let metrics: MetricsCollector | undefined;
let traceManager: TraceManager | undefined;
let commandSpan: ActiveSpan | undefined;
let runDirPath: string | undefined;
const startTime = Date.now();
--- code end ---

Affected: plan.ts, rate-limits.ts, validate.ts, status/index.ts, resume.ts, context/summarize.ts, doctor.ts (partial), pr/status.ts (partial — uses inline rather than the shared helper). This variable declaration block is a prerequisite to using flushTelemetrySuccess/flushTelemetryError but is not part of any shared abstraction.

The coordinator construction pattern appears identically in research/create.ts, research/list.ts, and status/data.ts:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
const coordinator = createResearchCoordinator(
  {
    repoRoot: process.cwd(),
    runDir,
    featureId,
  },
  logger,
  metrics
);
--- code end ---

In all three locations the arguments are identical in structure (repoRoot=process.cwd(), runDir, featureId, logger, metrics). The start.ts command uses a slightly different call site inside runResearchDetection, but the same pattern.

The doctor.ts success path manually replicates the full telemetry flush sequence (lines 213-246) rather than calling flushTelemetrySuccess:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
if (metrics) {
  const duration = Date.now() - startTime;
  metrics.observe(StandardMetrics.COMMAND_EXECUTION_DURATION_MS, duration, { command: 'doctor' });
  metrics.increment(StandardMetrics.COMMAND_INVOCATIONS_TOTAL, { command: 'doctor', exit_code: String(exitCode) });
  await metrics.flush();
}
if (commandSpan) {
  commandSpan.setAttribute('exit_code', exitCode);
  // ...
  commandSpan.end(...);
}
if (traceManager) { await traceManager.flush(); }
if (logger) {
  logger.info('Doctor command completed', {...});
  await logger.flush();
}
--- code end ---

This is the same ~30 lines that flushTelemetrySuccess encapsulates. The flushTelemetryError is already used by doctor.ts in its catch block, making the inconsistency more apparent.

Both start.ts and approve.ts contain the same settings validation block:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
if (settings.errors.length > 0 || !settings.config) {
  const message =
    settings.errors.length > 0
      ? settings.errors.join('\n')
      : 'Repository not initialized. Run "codepipe init" first.';
  // ...
  this.error(message, { exit: 10 });
}
--- code end ---

The identical ternary logic for deriving the error message from settings.errors appears in both commands. The resolveRunDirectorySettings function already returns errors and config — this guard should be part of a shared validate-settings utility.

In resume.ts the attachRateLimitWarnings method contains nearly identical 10-line blocks for 'github' and 'linear' providers:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
if (providerName === 'github') {
  if (!integrationBlockers.github) { integrationBlockers.github = []; }
  if (providerData.inCooldown) {
    integrationBlockers.github.push(`Rate limit cooldown until ${providerData.resetAt}`);
  }
  if (providerData.manualAckRequired) {
    integrationBlockers.github.push(`Manual acknowledgement required (${providerData.recentHitCount} consecutive hits)`);
  }
}
// identical block for 'linear' replacing 'github' with 'linear'
--- code end ---

The two blocks are copy-pasted with only the provider key name changed.

The block that constructs dag_metadata from planSummary.dag is copy-pasted between plan.ts buildPlanPayload and status/data.ts loadPlanStatus:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
if (planSummary.dag) {
  payload.plan_summary.dag_metadata = {
    ...(planSummary.dag.parallelPaths !== undefined && { parallel_paths: planSummary.dag.parallelPaths }),
    ...(planSummary.dag.criticalPathDepth !== undefined && { critical_path_depth: planSummary.dag.criticalPathDepth }),
    generated_at: planSummary.dag.generatedAt,
  };
}
--- code end ---

Both files do this identical spread construction. The type being constructed is similar in both locations.

The loadIntegrationsStatus function in data.ts contains two near-identical 50-line blocks for the GitHub and Linear integrations (lines 372-500). Both blocks: call RateLimitReporter.generateReport, extract provider data, build a rate_limit sub-object with remaining/reset_at/in_cooldown, check inCooldown and manualAckRequired to push warnings. The only real differences are the provider key string and the additional PR/issue metadata loading at the end of each block.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// GitHub block (lines 376-427)
const rateLimitReport = await RateLimitReporter.generateReport(runDir);
const githubProvider = rateLimitReport.providers['github'];
const github: StatusIntegrationsPayload['github'] = { enabled: true, warnings: githubWarnings };
if (githubProvider) {
  github.rate_limit = { remaining: githubProvider.remaining, reset_at: githubProvider.resetAt, in_cooldown: githubProvider.inCooldown };
  if (githubProvider.inCooldown) { githubWarnings.push(...) }
  if (githubProvider.manualAckRequired) { githubWarnings.push(...) }
}
// Linear block (lines 431-498) mirrors this exactly
--- code end ---

The string 'Repository not initialized. Run "codepipe init" first.' (or close variations) appears as a bare literal in approve.ts, start.ts, and validate.ts. This error message should be a named constant to avoid drift between instances and to allow easy global updates.

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// approve.ts line 142
: 'Repository not initialized. Run "codepipe init" first.';
// start.ts line 192
: 'Repository not initialized. Run "codepipe init" first.';
--- code end ---

The reviewer string splitting and trimming logic is duplicated:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
// pr/create.ts lines 253-256
const reviewersList = typedFlags.reviewers!.split(',').map(r => r.trim()).filter(r => r.length > 0);

// pr/reviewers.ts lines 118-122
const reviewersToAdd = typedFlags.add
  ? typedFlags.add.split(',').map(r => r.trim()).filter(r => r.length > 0)
  : [];
--- code end ---

Both blocks do the same comma-split + trim + filter-empty operation on a reviewer string.

The guard that logs unexpected (non-ENOENT) file read errors appears identically at least 8 times in status/data.ts:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
if (error && typeof error === 'object' && 'code' in error && error.code !== 'ENOENT') {
  logger?.warn('Failed to load X', {
    error: error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Unknown error',
    stack: error instanceof Error ? error.stack : undefined,
    ...,
    error_code: 'STATUS_X_LOAD_FAILED',
  });
}
--- code end ---

This guard appears in loadValidationStatus (lines 271-280, 293-301), loadPlanStatus (lines 231-240), loadTraceabilityStatus (lines 177-183), loadBranchProtectionStatus (lines 351-361), loadRateLimitsStatus (lines 551-558), loadResearchStatus (lines 576-585).

The getGitUser() private method in approve.ts:

--- code begin (reference only) ---
private getGitUser(): string {
  try {
    const email = execSync('git config user.email', {
      encoding: 'utf-8',
      stdio: ['pipe', 'pipe', 'pipe'],
    }).trim();
    return email || 'unknown';
  } catch {
    return 'unknown';
  }
}
--- code end ---

is a utility that could reasonably appear in other commands needing the git user identity. The startHelpers.ts already has findGitRoot() as a shared utility — getGitUser() should be there too rather than private to Approve.
